			<title><![CDATA[December '15 Release Thread]]></title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78295-December-15-Release-Thread&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Mon, 30 Nov 2015 09:09:31 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[The year is almost over. December is usually a pretty sparse month for new releases, as most of the publishers push to have their big titles ready in time for the rush of holiday shopping. We've got a couple standouts this year however.  
 
 
Setting aside my own bias, I think the biggest game this...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>The year is almost over. December is usually a pretty sparse month for new releases, as most of the publishers push to have their big titles ready in time for the rush of holiday shopping. We've got a couple standouts this year however. <br />
<br />
<br />
Setting aside my own bias, I think the biggest game this month is probably <b>Just Cause 3</b>. The previous game was a bit of a cult classic. These games are about filling open worlds with explosions, and they seem to be upping the ante and refining some of the formula. This is probably <i>the</i> action game to play this year, at least for those who just want dumb fun. Those wanting more direction or an interesting narrative may be disappointed, as that has never been the strength of the series.<br />
<br />
<b>Rainbow Six: Siege</b> is also due this month. This game has high aspirations and could be something great, but I haven't been following it closely enough to know if it will achieve this. It's basically an evolution of competitive shooter design like you would find in Counterstrike or something. Environments are destructible in ways they usually aren't in these games. I'm always a little nervous about games that come out in December (are they being rushed?) but this one definitely suffered a few delays. Will it be better for it? Or will it fail to distinguish itself?<br />
<br />
My personal pick of the month is <b>Xenoblade Chronicles X</b> for the Wii U. I do not know if it can possibly live up to expectations, but what little I've seen of it already is pretty intriguing. This might be the biggest jrpg of the year, and it's on a system not many fans of the genre are likely to own. For some, the previous game justified the Wii, and it will be interesting to see if the same is true now. Some of the design decisions seem questionable to me, but I want to see more. No other series does scale in quite the same way.<br />
<br />
<br />
Aside from those three games, we've got a few more jrpg ports on PC, including <b>Dragon Quest Heroes</b> and <b>Lightning Returns</b>. Oh right, and supposedly <b>Devil's Third</b> for the Wii U is going to come out. Remember Devil's Third? The ultra violent action game from Itagaki, the creator of Dead or Alive? No? Might be a reason for that. Buzz for this one seems to be negative. It's anti-buzz. It hasn't shown well I guess and for awhile it wasn't clear if it still existed. Worth keeping an eye on if you have a Wii U though.<br />
<br />
<br />
